Real-Time Pricing (RTP) is a core smart grid functionality that periodically relays pricing signals to end-users based on their fine-grained power consumption data. However, a growing concern revolves around potential information leakage from this consumption data. While existing solutions address this privacy concern by adopting information-theoretic and cryptographic techniques, including differential privacy and homomorphic encryption, we investigate Multi-Party Computation (MPC) to achieve privacy-preserving RTP. Despite extensive research in the MPC domain, the current techniques need to be reinvestigated for the problem at hand. In particular, we highlight that for RTP evaluations, the critical operation is division, where both the numerator and denominator are private. In such cases, the currently reported MPC methods use fixed-point arithmetic, approximations, and precomputations, resulting in large communication overheads and lower computational accuracy. This paper overcomes the state-of-the-art by introducing a novel MPC technique for precise division using IEEE 754 floating-point arithmetic, achieving RTP accuracy up to 10− 10 for a million consumers, an improvement of at least five orders of magnitude over existing MPC-based approaches. The proposed MPC-based RTP scheme ensures constant communication and computation overhead per consumer and provides formal security guarantees under real-world/ideal-world simulation paradigm. We evaluate the feasibility of our scheme through extensive experiments, including consumer-side validation with an in-house developed smart meter, demonstrating price stabilization and significantly higher accuracy than state-of-the-art MPC solutions.